No, apparently not. The creature just snarled and tried to fly directly toward Thassalin. Fortunately, Thassalin, despite his size, was agile enough to dodge, but Nyssi let out a cry as she nearly lost her grip on Thassalin's extremely smooth scales.
"HOW CAN WE KILL HER?" cried Nyssi.
"AIM FOR THEIR HEADS!"
"THIS WILL BE DIFFICULT!"
Thassalin zipped and then drew a circle closer to the mountain he called home. The dark beast followed, but soon slipped into panic when a fire ray struck her from behind. She had not noticed that she was no longer alone. She panicked even more when Thassalin slowed down and then hurled his tail at her head, diverting her course.
Snarling and growling, she flew upward and spat into the air. Everything suddenly turned dark, as if the monster had sucked the light from the sky and replaced it with a cloud of eternal night.
When he suddenly could no longer see anything, Thassalin attempted to retreat. He felt himself scraping along the tree canopy before finally crashing into an clearing. The beast seemed to know exactly where he had fallen and shot directly at him, dragging the black cloud with her.
"Kayel!" cried Tenuk as he slipped out of the cloud and began circling to scout for Nyssi and Thassalin in the darkness below. "What should we do now? Kayel…? Kayel, where are you?"
Below Nyssi painfully got to her feet. She was sure she had broken something, but her peculiar, supernatural healing powers were already beginning to take effect. Unfortunately, this did not apply to Thassalin. He leaned exhausted against the only tree that had not collapsed under his weight. Nyssi made every effort to get close to Thassalin, but she could hardly see two meters ahead. Everything was pitch black and enveloped in eerie shadows. And within this shadow something screamed and screeched.
A terrifying, armored tail crashed down beside Nyssi onto the ground and knocked her to the floor. However, she noticed that the tail was just swinging wildly and not attempting to hit her deliberately. The beast, or what little Nyssi could see and hear of it, growled and clawed at the shadows it had created. Something shot through the darkness, lunged at the monster, and confused it.
Suddenly, a gunshot cracked through the fog, and the monster fell silent, collapsed to the ground, and lay motionless. The darkness around them faded, and they saw what had happened: Standing on the beast was Kayel, holding his rifle heavily breathing.
"Thats was probably... the craziest shadow jump I've ever made... Thanto kat'olon..." Kabel gasped for air. His eyes glowed almost black, and a dark energy circled his body. But while he was still speaking, color returned to his armor, and his eyes regained their normal yellow hue.
It took Nyssi a moment to understand what had happened. They had all known that Kayel possessed these strange shadow powers. He used them rarely, as most found them eerie and quite frightening. But Nyssi had not known that Kayel could use these powers in any kind of darkness. And as Kayel behaved, it was clear he was obviously quite surprised.
"Are you okay?" it burst out from Nyssi.
"Yep, I'm okay. I've killed something, I'll be fine soon." Kayel examined his work, while Tenuk descended, landed beside him, and once again assumed his normal spastic form.
Now that the beast was no longer moving, they could better see what it was. Its skin was pitch-black and slimy, but the slime remained stuck to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, all ending in long, thin claws, and two straight horns stood out from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what the hell they were looking at, something screeched and leaped out from a nearby bush. It didn't reach them, however, because a familiar vehicle crashed into its side, causing the monster to slide to a stop in front of Nyssi's feet. Nyssi wanted to take no risks. She grabbed her shot gun, fired without thinking at its skull, and the creature died right there.
"Ups…", murmured Retvik from the driver's seat, before awkwardly turning off the engine and stepping out of the truck. "Uh, that wasn't really intended. Are you all okay?"
"you missed the whole action," scolded Tenuk. "Where were you?"
"I've all of you just left me standing. I came as quickly as I could…", sighed Retvik. "May I ask what terrible creatures these are?"
Retvik's question was fortunately answered by Thassalin, who had managed to get back to his feet. He was covered in cuts and scratches and seemed a bit dazed, but not seriously injured.
"YOU KILLED THE CORRUPTED ONES! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. BEINGS THAT WERE LEAVING HERE, WHEN THE CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
"Did you mean the terrible god-monster creature that we… helped to kill?" stammered Tenuk.
"YES. EXACTLY THAT. PERHAPS THERE ARE MORE. BUT I COULDN’T SHOOT IN THE HEAD. I DON’T HAVE A GUN. AND TWO AGAINST ONE IS UNFAIR, OR?“ Thassalin hobbled to Kayel and patted his head. “THANK YOU, LITTLE ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. ONLY NOT SO MURDEROUS AND NOT SO SKILLED IN KILLING ENTIRE UNIVERSES.”
"Um… thanks… I think…", shrugged Kayel. "So, are we done here?"
Nyssi shrugged her shoulders. She grabbed her camera and took a few photos of the now definitely dead creatures. Then she pulled out her favorite weapon, the ornate Death God dagger, and began sawing off one of the beast's horns. Afterwards, she moved on to the second one. But as Nyssi was just finished, the creatures suddenly burst into flames and turned into a pile of ash in an instant. The same happened to the horns she had cut off.
"So, that's now both practical and impractical…", sighed Nyssi. "But at least I have the photos, hopefully."
